{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_gann_ver01/data/sn83035565/00296026906/1910092901/0181.xml":{"full_text":"on. g\nOlANT f?i\namJMexico\n'-\"1\nHi -'I 1\n4 ,,'1 ?f\n1\n3jDjiJl4NZElTM4cDoia4L\nDirector o 64 J. Jtepartment\nm-r'A\",\" -,-tT ,Tv-r' Cr\n\n\"c. j STJ\ni\n!5\n-Zfeff JJJUIT PiAfif or- 4AJ UUJ,JfeVAUt\nwood. Apparently the presence of an excess of\ngypsum is prejudicial to the growth of the mes\nquite. The bottoms among the dunes have a dense\nvegetation as compared with that of the dunes\nthemselves. It Is characterized especially by the\npresence of a grama grass (Bouteloua). forming\nalmost a turf, and by frequent clumps of Ephedra\nof a grayish purple color at this season and with\nthreescaled nodes. These bottoms usually show\nno sign of moisture, but In two places we found\nwater holes, the water so alkaline that the horses\nwould not drink It at\nthe end of their first\nday's drive.\nProbably the most\nextraordinary product\nof the Sonora desert,\nwest of Torres, Mex-\nUCSON has a cli\nmate of a thor\noughly desert char\nacter, and a flora,\nincluding moun\ntains and plain,\nrich In species-and\ngenera. In addi\ntion to its situa\ntion in the heart\nof the desert of Arizona, it is cen\ntrally located, both as to position\nand transportation, with reference\nto the deserts of Texas, Chihua\nhua, New Mexico, California and\nSonora.\nThe University of Arizona, with\nits School of Mines, and the Ari\nzona agricultural experiment sta\ntion are located at\nTucson.\nNot the least of\nthe advantages of\nTucson as a center\nfor the activities of\nthe government\ndesert laboratory is\nthe broad-minded\ncomprehension of\nthe importance of\nthe purposes of the\nInstitution evinced\nby the citizens, ac\ncompanied by an\nearnest desire to co\noperate in its estab\nlishment. This ap-\npressed in the prac\ntical' form of subsi\ndies of land for the\nsite of the building\nand to serve as a\npreserve for desert vegetation, the Installation\nand construction of telephone, light and power\nconnections, and of a road to the site of the lab\noratory, about two miles from Tucson. This\nspirit of hearty co-operation has animated every\norganization in the city, and has enabled the lab\noratory to gain control of a domain of 860 acres,\nof the greatest usefulness for general experimen\ntal work.\nExtending northward for nearly 100 miles\nfrom El Paso Is the noted Jornada del Muerta\n(Journey of Death), which has a width of 30\nto 40 miles. It formed a portion of the route\nconnecting the earliest settlements along the Rio\nGrande, and here the traveler was compelled to\nleave the stream far to the westward, in its\ndeeply cut, inaccessible canyon, and toil for two\nor three days in the burning heat without water,\nexcept such as might be carried. It was for three\ncenturies one oi the most menacing and hazard\nous overland journeys to be encountered in the\nAmerican desert. Recent investigations, however,\nhave shown that the region traversed is In real\nity a basin, and that water is to be found, as in\nmany other deserts, within a reasonable distance\nof the surface.\nBeyond lies an equally remarkable desert, the\nOtero basin, which is the bed of an ancient lake,\nand is noted for a great salt and soda flat, a salt\nlake, and, most striking of all, the \"White Sands,\"\nan area of about 300 square miles covered with\ndunes of gypsum sand rislng to a maximum\nheight of 60 feet\nThe surface of the dunes is sparkling white, j\ndue to the dry condition of the; gypsum powder,\nbut a few inches, beneath it is of a yellowish or\nbuff color and is distinctly moist and cool to the\ntouch, even when the air is extremely hot.\nThe most characteristic plant of the dunes is\nthe three-leaf sumac (Rhus trilobata), which oc\ncure in the form of single hemispherical bushes\nfour to eight feet high, the lower branchesv hug\nging the sand. The plant grows vigorously, the\ntrunk at or beneath the surface often reaching\na diameter of three Inches. The binding and pro\ntecting effect of this bush is often shown in a\nBtriking manner when In the cutting down of an\nolder dune by the wind a column of sand may\nbe left protected above from the sun by the close\ncovering of the branches and leaves, and the sand\nId the column Itself bound together by the long,\npenetrating roots. One of these columns was\nabout 15 feet high from its base to the summit\nof the protecting bush and about 8 feet in diam\neter at the base.\nA marked peculiarity of the White Sands is\nthat a cottonwood is occasionally found in the\nlower dunes, reaching a foot in diameter, but sel\ndom more than 15 feet in height; yet at the same\ntime not a mesquite was seen. The mesqulte Is\na tree requiring less moisture than the cotton-\nI'M R?M\nIS?. 17 A\nW$tf tf'tty-; fW ti 'i nr. m.,i.. d\nm iiT, H Trail r 'ii ifi.\nII J&Z\nEchlnocactus was represented by a half-dozen\nspecies, of which one, E. grande, is undoubtedly\nthe most massive of all the genus, being as much\nas 8 or 9 feet in height and 30 or even 36 Inches\nin thickness, which, with the many convolutions\nof its surface, makes It a very grotesque feature\nof the scenery.\nE. flavescens forms small beads in clusters,\nwhile in E. robusta colonies 10 or 15 feet across,\nmaking mounds 2 or 3 feet high, Include hundreds\nof heads.\nNo systematic account of any desert is to ba\nfound n whicu the storage function appears so\nhighly developed and by so many species. Of\ncourse all of the cacti exhibit this feature in a\nvery marked degree, and a single plant of Pllo\ncereus fulviceps may retain Beveral hundred gal\nlons of water. The large stems of Yucca, which\nisa prominent member of the flora of the slopes,\n.Wi'ft 9.:'. V a\"\ni\nTV\" fr\ninmniMllLa-\ntv:.\n64\na sS. t& AT\ndJAf w Paimj JtfTfE Moirm as a Caxyojt\nGOZOJlAJHt IJSMT\nlco, is the guarequi (Ibervillea sono\nrae), a tendril-bearing plant whose\ninordinately thickened root and stem\nbase lies gray and half exposed upon\nthe ground beneath some trellising\nshrub. These tuberous formations may be seen\nduring the dry season lying about wholly unan\nchored, as tho slender roots dry up with the close\nof tho vegetative season, which lasts but a few\nweeks.\nIn February, 1902, some of these tubers were\ntaken to the New York Botanical garden, and a\nlarge specimen not treated in any way was\nplaced in a museum case, where it has since re\nmained. Annually, at a time fairly coincident\nwith the natural vegetative season in its native\nhabitat, the major vegetative points awaken and\nsend up a fe,w thin shoots, which reach a length\nof about two feet only, since they do not obtain\nsunlight. After a period of a few weeks they lie\ndown again and the material in them retreats to\nthe tuber to await another season. Seven periods\nof activity have thus been displayed by this speci\nmen with no apparent change in Its structure or\nsize. It does not seem unreasonable to suppose,\ntherefore, that the guarequi is a storage structure\nof such great efficiency that water and other ma\nterial sufficient to meet the needs of the plant\nfor a quarter of a century are held in reserve\nin Its reservoirs.\nThe morning-glory (Iphomoea arborescens) Is\nhere a tree 20 to 30 feet high, with smooth,\nchalky gray trunk and branches. During Febru\nary it is leafless throughout, while its large white\nflowers open one by one on the ends of the naked\nbranches. From Its white bark the tree Is some\ntimes known as palo bianco, and from the gum'\nor resin, which exudes from incisions made in it\nfor. the purpose and which Is used as incense in\nreligious ceremonies, it Is also called palo aanto.\nOne of the striking features of the Tehuacan\ndesert of southern Mexico Is tEb extreme locali\nzation or strictness of colonization exhibited by\nmany species which are found to cover an area\nof a few square yards, the face of a slope, the\ncrest of a cliff or the floor of a barranca, with no\noutliers and with the nearest colony perhaps\nmany miles away.\nThe Cactaceae are more abundant here than\nIn any other part of the world yet visited, sev\neral of the species being massive forms.\nCephalocereus macrocephalus is a tall species\nof tho massiveness of the saguaro, and like it\nhaving a central shaft bearing numbers of\nbranches which are more closely appressed. It\nwas seen only along the cliff near the Rancho\nSab Diego, along the eastern edge of the valley.\nPilocereus fulviceps, of more general distribu\ntion on slopes, has a series of branches, in many\nInstances 40 or 50 in \"number, densely clustered\nand arising from a short trunk, which barely rises\nfrom the ground before It branches.\n1\ns4 -\"l.\nfunction to this pur\npose to some extent,\nwhile the fleshy\nleaves of Agave\nmarmorata and oth\ner species and of\nHectla, are essen\ntially storage or\ngans for reserve\nfood and surplus\nwater. Here is also\na Euphorbia and a\nPedilanthus, with\nthick upright cylin\ndrical stems, In\nwhich the storage\nfunction Is made\nmore effective by\nthe possession of a\nthick milk juice.\nAs one proceeds\nto the ancient ruins\nof Mltla, 36 miles\nto the southeast\nward of Oaxaca, the\nfnoMA. Cactus 1\naridity increases until in the vicinity of the ha\ncienda of that name extreme desert conditions\nare found. The ancient structures hero are in\ndicative of a type of civilization characteristic ol\nthe desert, in which co-operation or communism\nwas carried to as great lengths as it must have\nbeen in the pueblos of the northern deserts in\nAmerica.\nOne of the most difficult problems to solve is\nthat of transportation In the desert, and there are\nextensive areas In American deserts that have\nnot yet been systematically explored by reason\nof this condition.\nA comprehension of the part that water plays\nin existence and travel in the desert is to be\ngained only by experience. Some of the native\nanimals, such as mice and other small rodents,\nhave been known! to live on hard seeds without\ngreen food for periods of several months, or even\nas long as two or three years, and nothing in\ntheir behavior indicated that they ever took liquid\nIn any form.\nDeer and peccary are abundant in deserts in\nSonora in which the only available supply of open\nwater is to be found in the cacti.\nMan and his most constant companion on the\ndesert of America, the horse, are comparatively\npoorly equipped against the rigors of the desert\nA horseman, may go from the morning of one day\nuntil some hour of the next in midsummer and\nneither he nor his horse will incur serious dan\nger; experiences of this kind are numerous. If\nthe traveler Is afoot, abstinence from water from\nsunrise to sunset Is a serious Inconvenience to\nhim, and if he continues his journey, the follow\ning morning his sufferings may so disturb his\nmental balance that he may be unable to follow\na trail, and by the evening of that day, If he has\nnot come to something drinkable he may not rec\nognize the friendly stream in his way. Instances\nare not unknown in which sufferers from thirst\nhave forded streams waist deep to wander out on\nthe dry plain to grisly death.\nScouting Indians have long used the bisnaga.\nand a drink may be obtained in this manner by a\nskilled operator In five to ten mlnUes. Some trav\nelers are Inclined to look with much disfavor onf\nthe liquid so obtained, but it has been used with-'\nout discomfort by members of expeditions from\nthe desert laboratory. That it Is often preferred\nby Indians to fair water is evidenced by the fact\nthat the Whipple expedition found the Mohaves\nnear the mouth of the Bill Williams river, in\n1853, cooking ducks and' other birds in the juice\nof these plants by means of heated stones\ndropped into the cavity containing the pulp.\nTHE INDISPENSIBLE MAN\nTHE MARKETS\nCincinnati Live Stock.\ni\nState News\n3)\nNow and then a government clerk\nS dies in a secondary position and lit-\ntie note is taken of his death berond\nthA hare comment that he served vir\ntually a lifetime in a certain capacity.\nIn a way this may be a reflection on\nhis usefulness. Probably men like\nThomas P. Cleaves, who was clerk of\nthe senate committee on appropria\ntions for 37 years. And their relative\nobscurity pleasant. He began work,\nas clerk of the committee in 1873,\nwhen Senator Morrill of Vermont was\nIts chaidman, and continued to the\nend of Senator Aldrich's chosen time\nfor retirement. He saw new senators\ncome and veteran senators go, and\nalike he outstayed them. They had\nthe honors and the victories and the\nfame, but he was indispensable. The\nsense of knowledge and authority over\nhis superiors which such a man pos\nsessed, aloof from political changes,\nwas perhaps his best reward. He was\nneither an accident nor a great states\nman, but a plain necessity. In the\nvarious departments of the govern\nment such men are not infrequent\nThey are unknown to the public, their\nservices attract no attention outside\ntheir sphere, but they are the infalli\nble parts of the machinery when ad\nministrations change. It is often hard\ner to fill their places than to step a\ngap in the cabinet,\nRaised Skyward.\nThe suburban man was all sym\npathy. \"What's the trouble, my dear?\" he\nasked as he came home and found his\nwife in tears.\n\"T-trouble enough,\" sobbed his\nyoung wife, \"you k-know that Ave\nd-dollar incubator the man sold me?\nWell, it exploded today and blew\nall the chickens through the roof.\"\n'Oh, well, cheer up, Martha. The\nman said k would raise chickens, and\nyou see H did.\"\nOver the State\nMansfield. After a most delight\nful day at Niagara Falls, the for\neign delegates to the International\nPrison congress, and the American\ndelegates who are escorting them on\na tour of this country, arrived in\nMansfield at 7 a. m., September 22.\nThey had been invited by Gov\nernor Harmon, on behalf of the peo\nple of Ohio, to inspect the state re\nformatory here, which is considered\none of the best institutions of its kind\nin America. The special train stopped\nclose to the reformatory and the\nparty went directly to the institution\nfor breakfast as the guests of Supt.\nJ. A. Leonard and the board of man\nagers. The entire morning was then\ngiven up to an inspection of the re\nformatory and its methods.\nFremont. A business war between\nthe cities of Toledo and Fremont is\nImpending as a result of Fremont's\nultimatum sent to Toledo ordering\nToledo to keep hands off in the fight\namong northwestern Ohio cities to\nobtain the site for the new normal\nschool to be established by the state,\nor suffer the consequences. Toledo,\ncharges the Business Men's Protective\nassociation, the organization in Fre\nmont which corresponds to chambers\nof commerce in other cities; has been\nbooming Perrysburg, about 12 miles\nsouth of Toledo.\nCincinnati. The suspension of one\npoliceman, against whom accusa\ntions had been made, and the broad\nening of the scope of the inquiry\nfrom the city hall to the grand jury\nroom were among the developments\nin the investigation of alleged graft\ning in police circles in Cincinnati.\nYoungstown. Officers were elected\nin this city by the high court\nIndependent Order of Foresters of\nOhio in annual convention. Opposi\ntion to the administration was sup\npressed by the unanimous re-election\nof High Chief Ranger M. C. Burrler\nafter the insurgents withdrew the\nname of William Willfeld of Cleve\nland. Following are the officers\nchosen: High chief ranger, M. C.\nBurrier, Zanesville; vice high ranger,\nW. G. Tock, Cleveland; high secretary,\nB. F. Hannum, Cleveland; high treas\nurer, William O. Wright, Cleveland;\ncounsellor, J. L. Streneck, Lorain;\nhigh physician, Dr. W. H. Horr, Cleve\nland; high auditors, M. D. McCorkle,\nWarren and John Vance, Akron.\nCincinnati. President W. H. Taft,\nIn a speech at the Ohio Valley\nexposition, favored improvement of\nthe Ohio river along systematic lines.\nHe attacked present piecemea. appro\npriation methods. Old friends and\nneighbors greeted him with \"Hello,\nBill,\" and other familiar names He\nappeared to enjoy the familiarity.\nMassillon. Compelled at the point\nof a pistol to' stand in the cen\nter of the depot floor with his hands\nabove his head, A. E. Clampton, ticket\nagent for the B. O. railroad at\nBeach City, watched two masked men\nrifle the company's safe and remove\neverything of value from his clothes,\nIn all 25 in cash and Clampton't\nwatch were taken. Threatening to\nshoot if he moved within half an hour\nafter their departure the two burglars\nbacked out of the station.\nRavenna. L. C. Dodge, 90, one ol\nRavenna's oldest citizens, is dead\nhere. Mr. Dodge had been a merchant\nhere for over 50 years and was a\nprominent horseman in his earliet\ndays. He was the oldest continuous\nbusiness man here.\nEast Liverpool, Under the auspices\nof the East Liverpool Historical so\nciety the marker designating the. spot\nwhere Gen. John Morgan, the Confed\nerate cavalry raider, surrendered, was\ndedicated near West Point, seven\nmiles from this city.\nSteubenville. Mrs. W. B. Smith ol\nthis city was notified that she was\none of 20 heirs to an estate of $250,000\nleft by Mrs. Lopetta Wyman at Pekln,\n111. The bequest was unexpected.\nEast Liverpool. William E. Tryke,\n17 years of age, employed at the\nKlondike pottery, is dead here follow\ning overindulgence in peaches and\nbuttermilk. eRturnlng from his work\na few days ago he partook of many\npeaches. Warned to desist,' he filled\nhis pockets and continued eating as\nhe pitched a game of quoits. At the\nevening meal a short time later he\ndrank large quantities of cold butter\nmilk. Efforts to allay his suffering\nfailed and he died in great agony.\nCleveland. Just as moderate suc\ncess was in her grasp, after years\nof hardship and ill health, Mrs.\nClara Flachbarth, 42, died after drink\ning a cfuantity of carbolic acid in mis\ntake for medicine. The woman was a\nwidow.\nCincinnati. A public hearing has\nbeen started of the charges which\nhave been made in Cincinnati\nagainst certain members of the police\ndepartment by James Mulligan, pro\nprietor of a hotel and saloon at Long\nworth and Central avenues. Mulligan\ncharges that the police department,\nthrough Inspector James Casey and\nother members, has collected in the\npast ten years more than $500,000\nfrom the saloonists, divekeepers and\nproprietors of resorts in this city.\nYoungstown. David Welch, 35,\nyard master of the Pennsylvania rail\nroad at Girard, lived ftr three hours\nafter both legs and his left arm had\nbeen cut off, dying then at the City\nhospital here. He had crawled under\na car to show some workmen how to\nmake some repairs, when another\nwas backed down on it\nNcrwalk. The fact that $900 worth\nof unmounted diamonds that had been\nshipped by a New York firm of dia\nmond merchants to the C. F. Jackson\nCo., this city, were stolen from the\nexpress safe of the American Express\nCo., has just become known.\nMarion. R. A. Parrott of Bucyrus\nsuffered a broken leg and other seri\nous injuries and his wife and Mr. and\nMrs. E. Hall were slightly injured\nwhen their automobile skidded and\nturned turtle on the Delaware road\nnear here.\nCircleville. John Allen, 26, a farm\ner, was instantly killed. The team he\nwas driving became frightened at an\nautomobile, and when Allen turned\nthe horses into the bridge which\ncrosses Scippo creek, tho wagon\nstruck the side of the bridge, throw\ning Allen to the floor ot the wagon\nbed, where his skull was tKUshed.\nCattle Shippers $5.75a6.75, butcher\nsteers, extra $6a6.25, good to choice\n$5.45a5.90, heifers, extra, $5aC23, good\nto choice $4.25a4.90, cows, extra $4.65\na4.75, good to choice $4a4.60. Bulls\nBolognas $4a4.65, fat bulls $4.50a\n$5. Calves Extra $10, fair to good\n$8.50a9.75. Hogs Heavy, $9.10a9.25,\ngood to choice packers and butchers\n$9.40a9.45, mixed packers 9.35a9.45,\ncommon to heavy fat sows $6.50a8.50,\nlight shippers $9.25a9.45, pigs (110 lbs\nand less) $6a9.10. Sheep Extra $4.15\ngood to choice $3.35a4. Lambs\nExtra $7.10a7.15, good to choice $6.25\na7, yearlings $4a5.25.\nCincinnati Grain.\nWheat No. 2 red 99ca$1.01, No. 3\nred 92a98c. Corn No. 2 white 56a\n57c, No. 3 white 56a56c, No. 2 yellow\n66a56i&c, No. 3 yellow 55Via56c, No. 3\nmixed o5aS6c, white ear 58a60c, mixed\near 58a60, yellow ear 58a60c. Oats\nNo. 2 white 37837, No. 3 white 36a\n36c, standard whit 37a38c, No. 2\nmixed 33a34c, No. 3 mixed 33a33c.\nHay No. 1 timothy $18.25al8.75, No. 2\ntimothy $16.75al7.25, No. 3 timothy\n$15.25al5.75, No. 1 clover mixed $15.50\nal6, No. 1 clover $12al2.50. Malt\nSpring barley 87a90. Barley No. 2\nprlng 81a83c, No. 3 69a76c. Rye\nNo. 2 75a77c, No. 3 73a74c.\nCincinnati Miscellaneous.\nSutter Extras 31c lb, firsts 30c,\niancy dairy 22c. Poultry Hens\n13c lb, spring chickens 13c, spring\nducks 12c, turkeys 20c, geese 6a7c.\nEggs Prime 24c doz, firsts 221c.\nApples $2a4.50 bbl. Huckleberries\n$4 bu. Peaches Northern Ohio \"AA\"\n$2.50 bu, \"B\" $1.75. Potatoes Home\ngrown $2.35a2.50 bbl, sweet, Virginia\n(yellow) $2a2.25 bbl, Jersey $2.75a3.\nPears California Bartlett $3a3.50 bu.\nPlums California $1.15al.25 4-basket\ncrate. Sugar Corn 5a6c doz. String\nBeans Homegrown $1.50al.75 2-bu\nsack. Tomatoes Homegrown 60a75c\nbu.\nClarksville Tobacco.\nClarksville, Tenn. Tobacco receipts\nIn the open market the past week were\n12 hhds., sales 25 hhds. Quotations:\nTrash at $5a5.50, low lugs at $5.75a\n6.25, common lugs at $0.25a6.75, me\ndium lugs at $6.75a7.50, good lugs at\n$7.50a8.25, low leaf at $Sa9, common\nleaf at $9.50al0, medium leaf at $10.50\nall.50, good leaf at $13. No offerings\nfor fine leaf or choice offerings.\nBUSINESS OUTLOOK MIXED\nSays Dun's Review, With Little to En\ncourage Speculative Enterprise\nat Present Time.\nNew York. R. G. Dun's weekly re\nview says:\n\"With crops aggregating large in\nquantity and value, in spite of the re\nduced yield of spring wheat; with pol\nitics becoming so intense and uncer\ntain as to make enterprise timid, and,\nwith railroads and shippers engaged\nin a dispute over rates, the business\noutlook is mixed, trade reaction being\nplain in some important directions,\nwhile at the same time there are\nstreaks of progress and activity.\n\"It is, a3 a whole, a waiting situa\ntion, with little to encourage specu\nlative enterprise until conditions, now\ndoubtful or unsettled, become more\nclearly defined.\n\"Interest in iron and steel has cen\ntered chiefly in predictions of an early\ngeneral reduction of prices of finished\nsteel products, which have been dis\ncussed, and the effect has been dis\nquieting, notwithstanding denials from\nwell-informed sources. Some conces\nsions have been granted from time to\ntime of late, but it has been officially\nIntimated that no change of policy\nwill be undertaken by the large pro\nducers. New business has diminished,\nbut, aside from railroad material, a\nproduction continues in finished lines.\n\"In the dry goods market the im\nprovement in silks and ribbons i3 con\ntinued, and a few mills are running\nfull and overtime. In woolens and\nworsteds the demand as a whole is\nbetter, yet orders are so small and\nIrregular that mills are unable to re\nsume operations in a large way.\n\"Cottons are generally in moderate\ndemand, and throughout the trade\nthere is a desire to confine oiders to\nactual requirements.\n\"Footwear conditions show a slight\nimprovement, but the actual volume\nof trade continues moderate. The\namount of new business, however, is\nsomewhat larger. There is a decided\nimprovement in the demand for sole\nleather, with larger sales, especially\nof oak sole.\"\nBusiness Failures.\nNew York. Bradstreet's report\nsays:\nBusiness failures in the United\nStates for the week ending Septenv\nber 22, were 190, against 210 last week\n171 in vine like week of 1909, 2G7 in\nrSOS, 166 in 1907 and 165 in 1906.\nBusiness failures In Canada for the\nweek number 22, which compare with\nSO for last week, and 37 in the like\nweek of 1909.\nWheat, including flour, exports from\nthe United States and Canada forhe\nweek ending September 22, aggregat\ned 1,583,668 bushels, against 2,174,053\nlast week and 2,973,601 this week last\nyear. F or the 12 weeks ending Sep\ntember 22, exports are 17,534,362 bush\nels, against 25,031,023 in the corre\nsponding period test year.\nCorn exports for the week are 299,\n266 bushels, against 174,079 last week\nand 94,418 in 1909. For the 12 weeks\nending September 22, corn exports are\n3,062,262 bushels against 1,235,36a\nlast year.\nBandits Held Up Traction Car.\nSt. Paul, Minn. Six armed bandits\nheld up a crowded interurban street\ncar, securing $180, fought their way\n4o the rear of the car, and made thelr\nescape,\" in broad daylight. The car\nwas a Minneapolis-bound interurban\nand the robbery occurred at 5 p. m.\nThe crowd in the aisle made no effort\nto stop the men. At Eleventh avenue\nthe men signaled the motorman to\nstop the car, and with knives still in\ntheir hands the m in backed down the\nplatform. The n m escaped before\nthe police arrived.\nElyria. A very peculiar nervous\ndisease, attracting much attention\namong the physicians of Lorain\ncounty, has afflicted five-year-etd Wil\nliam Bradwell for 18 months. When\nfirst taken to the Elyria hospital, the\nlad could neither walk nor talk. After\n15 months' treatment he has not re\ngained the use of his limbs, but ean\ntalk a little. The moment he gets ex\ncited, his body becomes rigid.\nColumbus. If no success hereafter\nattends bis most heroic efforts, The\nHarvester will go into winter quarters\nwith the trotting record for stallions\nfixed at 2 01. That's the time he made\nhere and over, too, a track too soft\nnext the pole for him to go the short\nest possible route.\nNewark. William Bolton, brother\nef Louis Bolton, who was indicted\nIn connection with the Carl Etbering\nton lynching, was arrested here fol\nlowing an attack on Grace Langdon\nof Coney Island, N. Y. The girl was\nbeaten with a club, but her life prob\nably was saved by a large \"rat\" in her\nhair which stopped the force of the\nblows. Her condition is serious.\nRobbery is believed to have been the\nmotive of the attack.\nToledo. Instant dismissal from the\npolice force of the city of Toledo is\nto follow interference by any officer\nwith any one who is making a speech\nin Toledo, no matter the time, or\nplace, or crowd. Mayor Whitlock di\nrected Safety Director J. J. Mooney\nto promulgate this order. Coincidental\nwith the mailing of this letter went\nanother one to William Patterson, a\nSocialist, carrying with it the official\napology of the city through the mayor\nbecause of the indignity heaped upon\nhim through his arrest while he was\nspeaking before a crowd in Summit\nstreet.\nCincinnati. Harry A. Rheinstrom,\nson of the millionaire Cincinnati dis\ntiller and husband of Edna Lof\ntus, has been declared insane.\nHe has been removed to an asy\nlum at Oakland, Cal., and in conse\nquence of his violent condition has\nhad to be placed in a padded cell. His\npretty English wife, whom he married\nafter meeting her in Rector's, New\nYork, after she had had him freed\nfrom the asylum in which his family\nhad placed him on account of his in\nfatuation for her, is here and is deeply\ndistressed.\nDayton. Starting from the test\ning ground at Simms Station,\neight miles east of Dayton, Orville\nWright made a flight along the course\nof Mad river to this city, circled over\nthe buildings of the fall festival expo\nsition and extended the flight over\nthe business portion. This is the first\ntime an aeroplane has been driven\nover so perilous a route. He made\nthe circle over the city at an altitude\nof about 2,500 feet and the round trip\nbetween Dayton and the testing\nground in 21 minutes.\nAkron. Coroner H. S. Davidson\nIs diligently investigating the death ot\nMrs. John Zimmerly, wife of the sec\nretary and treasurer of Zimmerly\nBros. Co., which occurred on the\noperating table at the office of Lyman\nD. Triplett, magnetic healer. Triplett\nin telling of the death said: \"I had\njust told Mrs. Triplett the treatment\nwas finished and she was about to get\nup from the table when she threw up\nher hands and fell back on the table\nand died.\" According to members of\nher family Mrs. Zimmerly's exact ail\nment was not known.\nCleveland. Frances Puelo, an Ital\nian woman, aged 45, was murdered in\nher room in the Italian settlement.\nKenton. A few v days ago John\nWood of Alger advertised in a local\npaper for a wife. Later he met a\nwoman in this city who had answered\nthe ad and they were married.\nKenton. Alleging wilful absence\nfor a period of three years, Mrs. Ralph\nParlette, wife of the noted humorist,\nhas commenced suit for divorce here.\nWellston. Sentenced to attend Sun\nday school ever Sabbath for one\nyear, and to take his family\nwith him, Isaac Wickline, a miner of\nWalnwright, will move to this city\nthat he may comply with the terms ot\nthe court's decree. Wickline, in po\nlice court, was convicted on four\ncharges, carrying heavy penalties.\nMayor Elmer E. Gillingham made the\ndefendant promise to abstain from the\nuse of liquor for two years and to at\ntend Sunday school. Wickline's fam\nily consists of a wife and six children.\nWashington, D. C. The popula\ntion of Canton, O., is 50,217, an in\ncrease of 19,550, or 63.7 per cent, a;\ncompared with 30,667 in 1900. The pop\nulation of Cambridge, O., is 11,327, as\ncompared with 8,241 in 1900.\nOberlin. President Henry Church\nIll King is of the belief that\nthe difficulties which have arisen\nIn the college the past college year\nduring his absence abroad will right\nthemselves without legislation if pre\nsented fairly to the students, with\nwhom they are concerned. \"Legisla\ntion is of little value in itself,\" he\nsaid. \"I rely on the men themselves\nto face these questions and to settle\nthem as they should be settled.\"\nLma. Two passengers were in\nstantly killed and a score injured, sev\neral probably fatally, when the bag\ngage car and day coaches of an east\nbpund Erie train, the Chicago-New\nYork fast line, plunged down an em\nbankment and into the Auglaize river\nat Conneaut, O., ten miles west of\nLima. Spreading rails caused the\nwreck.\nLima. Samuel W. Ferguson, septu\nagenarian, wras convicted of murder\nIn the second degree. Ferguson shot\nand killed a neighbor, Daniel McGriff,\nlast May because of an unpaid gro\ncery bill.\nToledo. Fifteen days after Mr.\nand Mrs. Otto Snyder of this\ncity exchanged jobs, the husband tired\nof tho bargain and was glad to go\nback to his own position. Snyder is\na rural mail carrier working out of\nEast Toledo. He taught his wife the\nroute several days before going on\nhis vacation. According to the postal\nregulations, the rural mail carriers are\nobliged to secure substitutes in their\nabsence. Snyder's choice was his\nwife. While Mrs. Snyder was engaged\non the route for two weeks, Mr. Sny\nder stayed at home, washed dishes,\nwept and scrubbed.","height":"30004","width":"21100"}}
